/- This theorem states that for a sequence of states `ρ^n` and a sequence of measurements `σ''_n`, the limit of the logarithm of the ratio of the probability of getting the correct measurement result to the probability of getting the actual measurement result, divided by `n`, is less than or equal to the difference between the rates of measurement error for the two sequences plus twice the square root of the product of the error rates. This is a key result in the analysis of the efficiency of measurement strategies in quantum information theory. -/
theorem qLimit_le : ∀ (i : ι) (inst : UnitalFreeStateTheory ι) (ρ : MState (H i)) (σ : (n : ℕ) → ↑IsFree) (ε : Prob) (hε₁ : 0 < ε) (hε₂ : ε < 1) (hR1 : @SteinsLemma.R1✝ ι inst✝ i ρ ε < @SteinsLemma.R2✝ ι inst✝ i ρ σ) (hR1ne : @SteinsLemma.R1✝ ι inst✝ i ρ ε ≠ ⊤) (hR2ne : @SteinsLemma.R2✝ ι inst✝ i ρ σ ≠ ⊤) (hε₀ : 0 < @SteinsLemma.ε₀_func✝ ι inst✝ i ρ ε σ ε) (m : ℕ) (hm : m ≥ 1 ∧ 𝐃(statePow ρ m‖↑(σ m)) / ↑m < @SteinsLemma.R2✝ ι inst✝ i ρ σ + ↑⟨@SteinsLemma.ε₀_func✝ ι inst✝ i ρ ε σ ε, ⋯⟩) : Filter.liminf (fun n => (OptimalHypothesisRate ((ℰ n) (statePow ρ n)) ε (@SteinsLemma.σ''✝ ι inst✝ i ρ ε m σ n)).negLog / ↑n) Filter.atTop ≤ ↑(ENNReal.toNNReal (@SteinsLemma.R1✝ ι inst✝ i ρ ε))

